In this article, the author reflects on the unity breakfast named after Dr. and Mrs. King and the anniversary of the march in Selma. They acknowledge the absence of Reverend C.T. Vivian, Reverend Joseph Lowery, and Congressman John Lewis, who were preachers of the social gospel and architects of the 'Beloved Community.' The author highlights the historical struggle for Black Americans to exercise their right to vote, facing white supremacy and discriminatory practices. They mention the passing of the Voting Rights Act in 1965, which was a significant milestone in dismantling barriers to voting. However, they note that Republicans have continuously chipped away at the act, and the Supreme Court's decision in 2013 further weakened its protections. The author emphasizes the importance of voting, especially in light of the events of January 6th, when the Capitol was attacked. They express concern about the ongoing assault on the right to vote in state legislatures across the country. The author calls for the passage of the For the People Act of 2021 and the restoration of the Voting Rights Act. They also mention signing an executive order to make it easier for eligible voters to register and improve access to voting. The article concludes with a reminder from Congressman John Lewis to stay focused on the work of healing and uniting the nation and the belief that all individuals should be treated equally.